Replication Report on Renshon (2014)

Sean Hughes

Abstract

I replicate and expand upon the work in “Physiological Arousal and Political Beliefs” (CITATION) using data and replication code from the Harvard Dataverse (CITATION). In this paper Renshon, Lee, and Tingley explore the effects of incidental emotions on political beliefs. Specifically, by showing that heightened physiological reactivity, measured by SCL, mediated the relationship between anxiety and anti-immigration attitude, they are able to provide evidence that emotions incidental to the decision process can have important effects on our political beliefs.

I replicate 2 figures and 1 table from the article (located in the Appendix below). I also test the results of the study using alternative modeling techniques.

Extension Analysis

Goals

I will further explore the studies findings regarding the Effects of Physiological Arousal on Immigration Preferences. Specifically, this means comparing the significance of treatment vs. the responses to the immigration questionare. We take these variables and run a series of models to verify the robustness of the results.

Conclusion

The authors are correct in stating that there is a significant causal link between treatment (Given as a pretreatment video) and SCL (Appendix figure 1). They are also correct in stating that there is a significant link between SCL and immigrtion preferences (Extension 1). Despite these two claims, they fail to demonstrate the effects of anxiety on political beliefs.

Extension 1: Basic Linear Model

Using the main results table (Appendix Table 1) the authors claim that skin conductance reactivity is a significant predictor of immigration preference. Note that the authors of the paper choose to filter out data from the “RELAX” condition, citing that the results remain unchanged if included. We will include the RELAX condition and combine the 3 treatments into a binary variable with the following values: - 1 if treatment condition is Anxiety - 0 if treatment condition is Neutral or Relax

Model 1

A linear model of the video treatment condition (Relax, Neutral, or Anxiety) versus Skin Conductance readings.

Model 2

A linear model of the video treatment condition versus postreatment Immigration questionare responses.

Model 3

A linear model of Skin Conductance versus postreatment Immigration questionare responses.

Model 4

A linear model of the video treatment condition versus Skin Conductance readings and a variety of covariates from the pretreatment survey. The “Conservative” dummy variable was created by selecting all answers to the Ideology section of the pretreatment questionare that leaned conservative (responses were ranked on a 1 - 7 scale with 1 being very liberal and 7 being very conservative). The “High Income” dummy variable was created by selecting all users who had an income of $80k annualy or greater. The “White” dummy variable was created by selecting all users who responded to the Race section of the pretreatment questionare and indicated that they identified as white.

Model 5

A linear model of the Skin Conductance versus postreatment Immigration questionare responses including a variety of covariates from the pretreatment survey.

Figure 2 Bayesian Model

We fit the data with a bayesian linear model using the SCL conductivity measurements as the only predictor. We see the posterior distribution which refers to the probability distribution of an unknown quantity when treated as a random variable.

Appendix

Figure 2: Skin Confuctivity Confidence Intervals

When calculating the mean points for the different treatments I receive different results than are demonstrated in the paper. However, these results still show the same trend as shown in the paper: that the anxiety video condition effectively causes the user to experience anxiety and that the relax condition causes the amount of anxiety to be reduced. These results assume that Skin Conductivity Reactivity is a reasonable gauge of anxiety as described in the paper.
